docs.abstract: In California, protesters have toppled statues of Junipero Serra, whose missions brutalized Native Americans. How should we think of him now?
docs.snippet: In California, protesters have toppled statues of Junipero Serra, whose missions brutalized Native Americans. How should we think of him now?
docs.lead_paragraph: Last week, a few hours after publishing an essay about American Catholics’ reaction to the Black Lives Matter movement, I received a flood of ill tidings via email. My correspondents’ anger was unrelated to the subject of my article, but was instead inflamed by a mention of Junipero Serra, a canonized Franciscan friar who founded Spanish missions throughout California in the  18th century.
